  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions spans several decades and involves international cooperation. Here's an overview:\n\n1. Early Developments:\n- 1970 Bank Secrecy Act (USA) was one of the first comprehensive anti-money laundering (AML) regulations\n- Established reporting requirements for financial institutions\n- Required documentation of large currency transactions\n\n2. International Milestones:\n- 1988 UN Vienna Convention against drug trafficking\n- 1989 Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established\n- Developed international standards for combating money laundering\n\n3. Key Legislative Periods:\n- 1990s: Expanded AML regulations globally\n- 2001 USA PATRIOT Act significantly strengthened money laundering prohibitions\n- Increased reporting requirements\n- Enhanced criminal penalties\n\n4. Major Legal Components:\n- Criminalizing money laundering\n- Requiring suspicious transaction reporting\n- Establishing customer due diligence protocols\n- Creating international information sharing mechanisms\n\n5. Recent Trends:\n- Increased focus on cryptocurrency transactions\n- Enhanced digital surveillance capabilities\n- More sophisticated international cooperation\n\nThe legal framework continues evolving to address emerging financial technologies and sophisticated laundering techniques.",
